<subSubSection id="8DC46548FFA3465793DEFE5CF149FE2D" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C56136C3FFA3465793DEFE5CF149FE2D" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="F7AAEAD1FFA3465793DEFE5CF23EFE08" bold="true" box="[199,334,439,464]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="02DE4D40FFA34657912FFE52F1E7FE08" authorityName="Miranda" authorityYear="2017" box="[566,663,441,464]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hybobathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avittatus">
<emphasis id="F7AAEAD1FFA34657912FFE52F1E7FE08" box="[566,663,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">avittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(without vittae) refers to the lack of vittate markings on the abdomen and should be treated as an adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8DC46548FFA3465793DEFE14F115FD15" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C56136C3FFA3465793DEFE14F115FD15" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,717]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="F7AAEAD1FFA3465793DEFE14F23FFDC0" bold="true" box="[199,335,511,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Comments.</emphasis>
It seems that most of the microtrichosity was obscured dorsally on the 
<typeStatus id="1A658861FFA3465797ACFDEBF795FDC0" box="[1205,1253,512,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">type</typeStatus>
specimen after dissection, but it is still possible to see the common boundaries of its typical distribution in the 
<taxonomicName id="02DE4D40FFA3465797FFFDCFF6EBFDE4" box="[1254,1435,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Hybobathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arx">
<emphasis id="F7AAEAD1FFA3465797FFFDCFF6EBFDE4" box="[1254,1435,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Hybobathus arx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. This species is readily distinguished from others of this group by the lack of vittae on the abdomen (
<figureCitation id="5DE52A46FFA346579627FDACF6FEFDB8" box="[1342,1422,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[153,1426,792,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,784,1816]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hybobathus avittatus sp. nov., male, holotype. a. Habitus, dorsal. b. Habitus, lateral. c. Head, frontal. d – h. Genitalia: d. Epandrium, dorsal. e. Epandrium, ventral. f. Hypandrium, ventral. g. Hypandrium, lateral. h. Hypandrium, basiphallus focus, lateral. bph: Basiphallus, ind: Ventro-lateral indentation of the hypandrium, pgt: Postgonite, sscl: Subepandrial sclerite, srs: Surstylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1035675/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 3a</figureCitation>
), and its genitalia, which is unique among the group due specially to its short and sub-triangular surstylus (
<figureCitation id="5DE52A46FFA346579632FD87F3D4FD70" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[153,1426,792,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,784,1816]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hybobathus avittatus sp. nov., male, holotype. a. Habitus, dorsal. b. Habitus, lateral. c. Head, frontal. d – h. Genitalia: d. Epandrium, dorsal. e. Epandrium, ventral. f. Hypandrium, ventral. g. Hypandrium, lateral. h. Hypandrium, basiphallus focus, lateral. bph: Basiphallus, ind: Ventro-lateral indentation of the hypandrium, pgt: Postgonite, sscl: Subepandrial sclerite, srs: Surstylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1035675/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs 3d &amp; e</figureCitation>
) (elongated and sub-oval on other species) and postgonite with abbreviated apico-dorsal extremity (
<figureCitation id="5DE52A46FFA346579627FD64F6E3FD70" box="[1342,1427,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[153,1426,792,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,784,1816]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hybobathus avittatus sp. nov., male, holotype. a. Habitus, dorsal. b. Habitus, lateral. c. Head, frontal. d – h. Genitalia: d. Epandrium, dorsal. e. Epandrium, ventral. f. Hypandrium, ventral. g. Hypandrium, lateral. h. Hypandrium, basiphallus focus, lateral. bph: Basiphallus, ind: Ventro-lateral indentation of the hypandrium, pgt: Postgonite, sscl: Subepandrial sclerite, srs: Surstylus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1035675/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Fig. 
<quantity id="02269B26FFA34657966EFD7BF6E3FD70" box="[1399,1427,656,680]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="3.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="g" value="3.0">3g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
) (extremity more robust on other species).
</paragraph>
